{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"028f0c56-c721-4889-adef-051043fed300","content":"Here's the diagnosis and recommendations:\n\n## Root Cause\n\nThe developer report confirms it: the overhead is **MSBuild process startup and project re-evaluation** on every `dotnet build` invocation. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping MSBuild loaded in-process. The `.csproj` itself is clean — nothing to optimize there.\n\n## Recommendations (in priority order)\n\n### 1. Use `dotnet watch` for the inner loop\nKeeps the build host alive and rebuilds on file changes — no repeated cold starts:\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\n### 2. Enable the MSBuild Server\nReuses an MSBuild server process across CLI invocations, eliminating startup overhead (available in .NET 8+):\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build\n```\nOr set it permanently in your shell profile. The first build is normal speed; subsequent builds skip process startup.\n\n### 3. Use the Terminal Logger (`-tl`)\nReduces logging overhead, which shaves off time on every invocation:\n```bash\ndotnet build -tl\n```\n\n### Summary\n| Approach | Best for | Saves |\n|---|---|---|\n| `dotnet watch` | Continuous edit-build cycles | Process startup + re-evaluation |\n| `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` | Ad-hoc CLI builds | Process startup |\n| `-tl` | All CLI builds | Logging overhead |\n\nThe biggest win is **`dotnet watch`** or **MSBuild Server** — both eliminate the exact overhead the report describes (process startup and graph re-evaluation), bringing CLI build times close to the Visual Studio experience.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c466ffea-5c61-4e7d-8710-81c04dec8326","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds even when nothing changed), while Visual Studio builds the same project nearly instantly.\n\nThe key insight here is understanding why Visual Studio is faster: VS uses an in-process MSBuild server that keeps the MSBuild process alive between builds, avoiding process startup and project re-evaluation overhead. The CLI, by default, starts a new MSBuild process each time.\n\nThe solution is to use the **MSBuild Server** (also known as the MSBuild build server or `dotnet build-server`), which was introduced to address exactly this problem. Starting with .NET 8, MSBuild supports a server mode that keeps the build process alive between invocations, similar to how Visual Studio works.\n\n\nTo enable this, I can set the `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` environment variable, which activates the MSBuild server for CLI builds and eliminates the startup overhead that's causing the slowdown.\n\nFor iterative development, `dotnet watch` is even better since it keeps the process alive between changes and automatically rebuilds when files change, avoiding repeated process initialization entirely.","outputTokens":1038,"requestId":"EC2D:310F9A:AE80BD:D837E8:6A012988"},"id":"36227a9a-b17e-485c-878d-3fa12171b450","timestamp":"2026-05-11T00:58:08.051Z","parentId":"cd56b498-4d93-4282-84eb-6e52aabfc1ce"}
